column168: Upon completion of filling the cargo tank, the driver failed to tighten a 3" washout cap that was on the top of the cargo tank.  While in transit the liquid inside the partially filled cargo tank surged against the loose washout cap and caused to cap to come off, splashing liquid onto the ground.  A small amount of contaminated soil was excavated and placed into 55 gallon drums.
column169: The driver involved in this incident has been removed from cargo tank operations and will be re-trained prior to resuming such operations.  It is recommended that all drivers of cargo tank motor vehicles receive a minimum of 24 hours of training with a supervisor.

DURIGN THE END OF THE PRELOAD SORT, PRELOADER DISCOVERED LEAKING PACKAGE PRIOR TO LOADING A PAKCAGE IN PACKAGE CAR.  PRELOADER THEN PLACED PACKAGE ON PRELOAD BELT AND NOTIFIED PRELOAD SUPERVISOR IN THE WORK AREA.  SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY SWITCHED OFF CONVEYOR BELT AND CALLED FIRST RESPONDER TO INSPECT PACKAGE.  FIRST RESPONDER NOTIFIED PUT ON PPE AND FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEETS.  FIRST RESPONDER INSPECTED THE PACKAGE AND FOUND THE SPILLED LIQUID WAS SUSPECTED TO BE MERCURY BASED ON THE COLOR AND TEXTURE OF THE SUBSTANCE.  FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE FIRST RESPONDER IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED PE WHO CALLED AN OUTSIDE RESPONDER TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP SPILL.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A THERMOMETER IN THE PACKAGE WAS DAMAGED DUE TO POOR PACKING.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS ON THE PACKAGE THAT INDICATED IT WAS HAZARDOUS.  THIS INCIDENT INVOLVED A NON-REGULATED QUANTITY OF MERCURY.  THIS REPORT IS BEING FILED IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 CFR 171.15 (C) AS THIS INCIDENT HAD BEEN PREVIOUSLY REPORTED TO THE NRC.

DRIVER LOST CONTROL AND VEHICLE OVERTURNED.  A PIECE OF METAL ON THE JWALL POKED A HOLE IN THE SHELL OF THE TRAILER.  RUBBING THE JWALL RUPTURED THE FUEL TANK AND IGNITED THE DIESEL FUEL.  THE TRAILER WAS LEAKIN GFOR AROUND 5 HOURS WHILE THE FIRE BURNED OUT.  SAND WAS USED TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT SPREAD AND BLOCK AND FREEWAY EXIT POINTS.  A VAC TRUCK FOROM WEST CENTRAL SERVICES ARRIVED AROUND 8:30 AND STARTED TO VAC UP PRODUCT AND SUCK UP ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKING PRODUCT

WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, WE OPENED DOOR TO TAKE OUT SHIPMENT AND SMELLED AN ODOR AND THE WOOD FLOORING WAS DAMP BACK TO THE DOOR.  THEIR IS A SLOW DRIP IN THE DRIVER FRONT CORNER OF THE TRAILER UNDERNEATH.  THE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED AND FOUND THAT THE PALLETS HAD SHIFTED AND EIGHT FIVE GALLON PAILS WERE DISCOVERED DAMAGED.  THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED AND THE DAMAGED PAILS WERE OVERPACKED INTO SALVAGE RECOVERY DRUMS AND PLACED IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BAY PENDING DISPOSITION.

column168: Driver loaded Sulfuric Acid @ Mosica Fertilizer in Mulberry, FL. After the loading process was completed the driver secure the dome lid opening and failed to properly secure the bleeder valve on the top of the trailer. The driver then departed the loading station inside the plant and proceeded to the gaurd house to scale out and receive his paperwork. The driver than deaprted the plant facility en-route to Mosica Fertilizer in Bartow, FL which is approx. 5 miles east of the loading location. When the driver arrived at the customers location he noticed that the side of the trailer was wet with product. It was determined that the driver had left the bleeder valve was in the open postion. The product was contained to the area around the scale area on an imprevious surface. CTL sent out personnel to clean up the spilled product.
column169: The bleeder valve system is connected into a brake-interlock system. It was determined that the driver slid the tires in order to get the trailer move which by-passed a safety systems. The driver in question violated CTL Company Policy and the Customer's in-plant policies, due to the severity of this situation the driver's employment has been terminated.

column168: Road driver noticed a material leaking out of trailer setting on the yard. He knew the trailer contained hazmat. Upon inspection of the freight, 1 pail was found cracked and leaking. column168: 55-gal plastic drum loaded into a trailer behind a large metal wood chipper. The drum was pushed against a metal protrusion on the chipper resulting in a puncture at the top of the drum but no immediate leak. As the trailer traveled across the country and arrived at our terminal in Carlisle, PA, it was discovered at unloading that the drum had been punctured and leaked a small amount onto the chipper. The chipper had some paint peeled off and was refused by the consignee so ABF will be paying for the cost of the chipper. The drum of hazmat was overpacked and accepted for delivery.
column169: Being more careful in the loading of hazmat and not forcing the material into a trailer.

column168: Drum was loaded behind another skid of freight in the trailer. The forklift operator picked the skid up with a forklift, when he did this, the skid rubbed against the drum and punctured it. The drum was turned on its side but had already lost a good amount of paint. The drum was donated to the local department of Parks and Recreation.
column169: The skid should not have been lifted immediately upon entry by the forklift operator. It should have been pulled away from the other freight before the blades were lifted.

column168: Drum was forked when the checker was offloading it from the trailer.
column169: Should not have forked the drum.

column168: Pail was found leaking at time of unloading. The reporting terminal stated that the pail appeared to have been punctured by a forklift blade during loading at previous terminal.
column169: Use proper loading techniques when loading with a forklift.

column168: Freight was delivered with no leaking or damaged bags. After delivery, a residue was noticed on the floor of the trailer. It was reported to me that the residue got wet thought it was not explained how it got wet. The material started bubbling. Soda ash was used to neutralize the product. The material was cleaned up and placed into a recovery pail. The pail was disposed of properly as waste.
column169: No known damage.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: Small amounts of black paint were found on trailer wall and floor when skid was being unloaded. Upon further investigation, it was found that several of the pails had loose lids on them allowing paint to splash out during transit.
column169: Cheap packaging should not be allowed to be used for any hazardous material and paint has always been allowed to be shipped in cheap packages that do not stand up to transportation.

column168: Freight was loaded on top of carton resulting in carton being crushed and an inner package being damaged. Inner damaged bottle was removed.
column169: Do not double stack heavy freight on top of lighter freight.

column18: 301 WEST BAY STREET BELL SOUTH TOWER
column168: CSXU 980956 NOTED LEAKING FROM REAR ONTO BUMPER BY PICK-UP DRIVER.  NO GROUND AREA AFFECTED.  CSXI HAZMAT AND CUSTOMER SERVICE CONTACTED.  RESPONSE TEAM FOUND 12 PLASTIC TOTES, 3 HAD NO GASKETS ON LIDS AND 9 LIDS WERE NOT PROPERLY TIGHTENED.  THIS ALLOWED LIQUID TO SLOSH OUT ONTO TOPS AND RUN DOWN SIDES OF TOTES.  APPROX. 1 GALLON TOTAL LEAKED.  GASKETS WERE ORDERED AND REPLACED, ALL WERE TIGHTEN, WIPED DOWN, AND LOADED BACK INTO FREIGHT CONTAINER.
column169: SHIPPER SHOULD CONFIRM AND IMPLEMENT PROCEDURES TO ENSURE CLOSURES ARE PROPERLY TIGHTENED BEFORE RELEASING FOR TRANSPORTATION.

column18: 301 WEST BAY STREET BELL SOUTH TOWER
column168: DCIU845115 NOTED LEAKING DURING OUT-GATE BY DRIVER.  UNIT PARKED INTO ISOLATED AREA, OIL DRY SPREAD OVER SPILL.  RESPONSE TEAM FOUND THE 20FT TANK DID NOT HAVE TOP OUTLET CAP FITTINGS IN PLACE.  IT WAS IN A PROTECTIVE BOX BESIDE THE CAP AREA.  LIQUID SLOSHED DOWN SIDES AND SPILLED ONTO ASPHALT AREA.  LESS THAN A PINT WAS RELEASED.  TOP OUTLET CAP WAS PLACED ON CORRECTLY, TANK WIPED DOWN, GROUND AREA CLEANED.  TWO ADDITIONAL TANKS, DCIU797152 AND DCIU749209 IN THIS SHIPMENT INSPECTED AND THE FOLLOWING FOUND: DCIU797152 WAS FOUND TO HAVE CAP FITTINGS COMPLETELY OFF; FITTINGS CORRECTLY PLACED; NO LEAKAGE.  TANK DCIU739209 WAS FOUND TO HAVE THE ENTIRE VALVE MOVE WHEN CAP WAS INSPECTED; VALVE REMOVED AND CORRECTLY REPLACED WITH CAP TIGHTENED; NO LEAKAGE.
column169: SHIPPER SHOULD IMPLEMENT AND CONFIRM PROCEDURES TO INSPECT TANKS FOR PROPER CLOSURES BEFORE RELEASING TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: SEMI-TRUCK WAS TRAVELING IN LEFT LANE HEADING WESTBOUND ON THE AIRPORT FREEWAY.  A PRIVATELY OWNED PICKUP TRUCK ENTERED THE FREEWAY ON THE ON RAMP AND FAILED TO CONTROL THE VEHICLE SPEED.  DUE TO THE ROAD CONDITIONS (WET), THE PICKUP TRUCK LOST CONTROL AND TRAVELED ACROSS ALL THREE LANES, COLLIDING WITH THE CENTER DIVIDE.  PICKUP TRUCK THEN COLLIDED WITH THE SEMI-TRUCK CAUSING THE DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE.  THE SEMI-TRUCK AND TRAILER LEFT THE ROAD SURFACE AT THE MACARTHUR BRIDGE OVERPASS LANDING ON THE ROAD SURFACE.  THE IMPACT OF THE CRASH CAUSED CATASTROPHIC DAMAGE TO THE TANKER RESULTING IN AN EXPLOSION AND RESULTING FIRE.  THIS RESULTED IN THE DEATH OF THE TRANSPORTATION DRIVER.  IT WAS DETERMINED THE PICKUP TRUCK DRIVER WAS INTOXICATED AND CHARGED WITH INTOXICATION MANSLAUGHTER.  IRVING FIRE DEPARTMENT IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND APPLIED FOAM SUPRESSANTS ONTO THE FIRE.  A LOCAL PRIVATE RESPONSE COMPANY WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO HELP IN CONTROLLING THE WATER RUN-OFF FROM FIRE CONTROL.  IMPACTED AREAS EFFECTED BY THE RELEASE WERE THE BELOW GROUND SURFACE STORM WATER SYSTEM AND ADJACENT SOIL AREAS IN AND AROUND THE IMPACT ZONE.  REMEDIATE EFFORTS AT THE AREA CONTINUED UNTIL JUNE 21, 2005.  PLEASE SEE ATTACHED SHEETS FOR ACCIDENT DIAGRAM AND PHOTOGRAPHS OF IMPACTED AREAS.
column169: IT HAS BEEN DETERMINED THAT THE TRANSPORTATION DRIVER DID ALL HE COULD TO PREVENT THIS INCIDENT.  TRANSPORTATION DRIVERS HAVE BEEN WARNED TO PAY CLOSE ATTENTION TO TRAFFIC ENTERING THE FREEWAY, AND TO LOOK FOR ANY TYPE OF ERRATIC BEHAVIOR, WHICH MAY CAUSE HARM TO THEIR VEHICLES.

column168: Driver was unloading product into customer's storage tank by use of a tractor mounted transfer pump. Shortly after engaging the pump the driver did not think product was flowing. He loosened on of the camlocks on the transfer hose at the customer's inlet to relieve what he thought was an airlock. As he did this, the second camlock released and allowed the transfer hose to come of the costermer's inlet. Product was flowing. Approximately 35 gallons spilled onto the customers floor before flow was stopped. Customer cleaned up the spilled product and the remainder was offloaded with no further consequences.

column169: PAILS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED AND BLOCKED, USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND OR DUNNAGE. WHEHANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAIN! GIN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND STACKING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS.

column168: ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHEN THE DOOR WAS RAISED ON THE TRAILER. ONE DRUM ON THE SHIPMENT APPEARED TO OF HAVE FALLEN OVER IN TRANSPORATION. AS IT WAS DISCOVERED LAYING ON ITS SIDE ON THE BACK LAFT REAR OF THE DOOR WAS BROUGHT DOWN AS SOON AS IT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. THE BILL WAS REVIEWED AND THE TRAILER ISOLATED IN THE BACK LOT BASED ON THE DIRECTION OF THE WIND. HAZMAT ONE WAS CONTACTED AND A TEAM WAS CALLED OUT. MILSTEAD ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALL OUT AND RESPONDED TIMELY. BREATHING APPEARATUSSES WERE USED AT TIME OF DISCOVER AND DURING THE CLEAN UP PHASE. THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A OVERPACK SALVAGE DRUM AND THE CLEAN UP MATTER WAS PLACED IN A FIVE GALLON SALVAGE PAIL. BOTH THE OVERPACK AND PAIL WERE PROPERLY LABELED AND PLACED IN THE HOU HAZMAT BAY TO AWAIT DISPOSITION.
column169: PROVIDED THE SHIPMENT WERE PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED THE INCIDENT WOULD HAVE NEVER OCCURED. THE OVERALLCOST OF CLEAN UP, AS WELL AS, THE COST ASSOCIATED WITH THE EXACT EXPRESS FAILURE WOULD HAVE NEVER OF HAPPENED.

column168: Drive called into the carrier HazMat Department to inform of the leaking drum upon arrival at the terminal in Concord, NC. Trailer was placed out of service for cleaning and removal of any residual material on trailer floor. Dispatching facility informed of incident and loader was retained in proper loading techniques to avoid container damage.

column168: Our driver arrived at Sunoco Refinery, Marcus Hook,PA to load spent sulfuric acid.  She loaded the trailer and thought the dome lid was secure.  She was not the driver that secured the dome, but another driver.  She left Sunoco scale and spent acid was draining out of the trailer spill dam tubes onto the scale.  She was unaware of the problem and proceeded up to CSX Railyard in Philadelphia.  There she was informed of the problem by CSX personnel.  Spillage was contained in box around trailer dome lid but a very small quantity of liguid ran thru the bleed off line which runs to the bottom of the trailer.
column169: We are taking additional measures to insure the all drivers check all trailer valves and openings and that those items requiring tool tightening are properly tightened.  Each driver is responsible for verifying that all openings are secure before driving away from the scale.  A check list will be issued and signed by the refinery operator and the driver before exiting the refinery thus assuring that no incident exists for any particular load.

column168: THE FIBERBOARD BOX DID NOT FAIL ALTHOUGH IT WAS LEAKING FROM THE INNER PLASTIC CONTAINER WHICH WAS A: 1H2/Y1.5/30/03..USA/AB1399. During a routine stop the driver noticed that there was a leaking container in his trailer.  The driver called Jevic Hazmat (JHM) to notify them of the  spilled material.  After research JHM called SRM Environmental (SRM) to dispatch a crew to clean up the spill.  SRM arrived on site at 6:00 p.m. to clean up the spill.  The spilled material was cleaned up with a clay absorbent and packed into a drum. The contaminated area was cleaned up with a water/sodium hydroxide mixture per the MSDS.  The decon liquid was also packed into a drum.  The damaged container was overpacked into a salvage drum.  All remaining freight was wiped down with the decon liquid mixture.  All of the spill clean up material was transported back to Jevic’s Conley, GA facility.    Once the trailer arrived in Conley, GA it was taken out of service. It will be sent to a truck wash for total decontamination before being placed back into service.
column169: The facility was sent a copy of the report.  The loaders will be counceled.  Follow up will be documented. Appropriate discipline will also be documented.

column168: A tanker truck heading south on Highway 61 attempted to turn left onto Sherwood Commons Street in Baton Rouge, LA.  The tanker rolled over.  Petron personnel in alexandria received the call at 0845 and dispatched their emergency response team.  At 0900 the state police emergency response hotline was notified.  The north bound lane of Hwy 61 between Seigan Lane and Southpark Drive was closed until 15:30.  When Petron arrived on the scene, Baton Rouge Area Mutual Aid System (BRAMAS) were already on the scene.  BRAMAS member, ChemNet, drilled openings into the sides of the tanker with an air drill.  Product was pumped out of the tanker and into another.  Less than 15 gallons of diesel fuel was lost from the first compartment of the tanker.  Clean-up started as soon as wreckers were able to upright and move the truck and trailer.  Soil was excavated around the edge of the road and around a drain.  Diesel fuel on the road was adsorbed with oil dry.  Puddles of fuel was collected with a vac truck.  Fuel and water was collected with a vac truck from a concrete drainage ditch.  All material was disposed of at approved facilities.  Lousisiana State Police, Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality, and BRAMAS were on the scene.  Clean-up was completed at 18:00.  Total duration of the release was 7 hours.

SHORTER LOCAL POLICE AND ALABAMA STATE HIGHWAY PATROL CLOSED DOWN THE NB AND SB LANES OF TRAVEL, WHICH WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  NOT ABLE TO SPEAK TO ANYONE ON SCENE DUE TO THE CIRCUMSTANCES SURROUNDING THE LOSS, BUT IT IS OUR UNDERSTANDING THAT THE VEHICLE AND IT'S CARGO ARE BOTH A TOTAL LOSS. CARGO CONTENTS WAS 1 CRATE, WEIGHING 157 LBS.

column168: Material handler, using a forklift, was picking a waste order from a rack location.  The drums were double stacked on the ground under the rack when he attempted to back out of the location.  The bolt on the openhead drum caught the the front portion of the rack and pulled the drum to the ground.  The drum was pushed in around the tightening ring creating a small opening were the product escaped from the container.  For approximately 3 minutes 1 gallon of material poured onto the floor.  The leak was contained.  The drum was placed in an overpack.  The spill was cleaned up and properly disposed of.
column169: Openhead drums will now be positioned with the bolt facing inward or to the back.    Spill kits will be placed in stratigic position to maximize efficiency of containment & clean up in hazardous areas of the warehouse.  Suggestions will be made to use tighthead drums for future waste pickups.

column169: Carriers are responsible for ensurring there equipment is adequate for the material being shipped not just once per year but before each transport of hazardous materials.

column168: During the unloading of the Ethylene Glycol r/c#OWIX15121.  The operator began pressurizing the car to bottom offload the product.  The operator observed product spraying form the induction tube flange(Note the induction tube is not used to offload the railcar). The operator stopped the transfer.  Upon examination the bolts on the flange were loose.  The operator tightened the bolts, cleaned up the residue, and resumed the transfer without further incident.

column168: BNSF SWICH CREW REPORTED GATX 22620 LEAKING COMMODITY DURING MOVEMENT IN RAILYARD.  BNSF TRAINMASTER RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THAT GATX 22620 WAS OVERFILLED, AS THE COMMODITY WITHIN WAS ESCAPING FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE AND EVAPORATING.  A HAZARDOUS WASTE VAC-TRUCK WAS CALLED AND REDUCED APPROXIMATELY 2,200 GALLONS FROM GATX 22620; AND THIS OPERATION CONCLUDED BY 1320 HRS.  CDT, 5/11/05. THE REDUCED COMMODITY WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR PROCESSING.  AFTER THE COMMODITY WAS REDUCED FROM GATX 22620, IT WAS ALLOWED TO PROCEED TO THE CONSIGNEE FOR UNLOADING AND THIS OCCURRED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  SPILLAGE EVAPORATED.

column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED GATX40736 IN RAILYARD EMANATING PRODUCT ODOR. GATX40736 WAS THEN ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD AND MONITORED.  GATX40736 WAS RELEASED TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION AFTER NO FURTHER PRODUCT ODOR EVIDENT DURING MONITORING OBSERVATIONS.

column168: The chemical truck operator was in the process of doing post job checks when the valve at the bottom of one of the Vicon totes came off of the tote. The spillage happened in a time period of approximately 1 minute and was approximately 49 gallons. This was contained with portable containments, absorbent pads and dikes until disposal containers could be brought to the well site. The spilled material, soiled absorbent pads and contaminated soil was then scooped up and placed in labeled disposal barrels and transported back to yard for forwarding to disposal facility. The valve was screwed back into the tote tank prior to transporting tank to contain any Vicon residue.
column169: We conducted Safety Stand Down and discussed the need to pinpoint discharge valves and insure they are tight during inspections prior to loading.

column168: A driver loaded a 55-gallon drum of Norox CHP catalyst onto the trailer.  He soon noticed a small leak coming from the bottom of the drum.  He immediately took the drum back into the hazardous material storage room in our warehouse facility and positioned it on its side so that it would not leak any more.  It is estimated that less than one pint of product leaked out.  The spilled material was cleaned up and disposed of.  NAC received the drum filled with product from the supplier.  It is believed that the spill is the result of an object puncturing the bottom of the drum when it was placed on the floor of the trailer during loading.  The drum was placed in a salvage drum.
column169: We notified the supplier of the product about this spill and requested that it inspected all metal drums prior to transport.  North American Composites purchased the product from Norac, the supplier.  The product was shipped to and received by our facility in Garland, TX.  At the time the spill incident occurred, we were in the process of loading it onto our trailer so that we could deliver it to our customer.  NAC is a distributor of hazardous materials.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0630 ON MAY 11, 2005, PITT OHIO EXPRESS, LLC (OUR UNIT NUMBER D980 AND TRAILER 1728 WAS STOPPED IN TRAFFIC THAT WAS SLOWED FOR ENTRY INTO A CONSTRUCTION ZONE ON INTERSTATE 78 AT MILE MARKER 41.  ANOTHER CARRIER, OPERATING A TRACTOR-TRAILER, FAILED TO SEE US STOPPED AND REAR-ENDED THE LEFT REAR CORNER OF OUR TRAILER.  THE OTHER CARRIER PROCEEDED DOWN THE PASSING LANE RIPPING OPEN BOTH TRAILERS.  DURING THE COLLISION, THE OTHER UNIT, CARRYING NON-HAZARDOUS POWDER MATERIAL FORMED AN APPARENT DUST CLOUD AND AN EXPLOSION OF THAT DUST OCCURRED.  THIS DUST EXPLOSION IGNITED BOTH UNITS.  THIS IS THE ONLY THOUGHT TO WHY THE FIRE OCCURRED.  NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CONTAINERS WERE TORN OPEN DURING THE COLLISION AND THE FUEL TANKS WERE IN TACT ON BOTH UNITS.  DUE TO THE MATERIALS INVOLVED, THE DECISION WAS MADE TO LEAVE THE UNITS BURN THEMSELVES OUT TO AVOID ANY ENVIRONMENTAL CONTAMINATION.  THE FIRE WITH THE EXCEPTION OF FOUR CARTONS OF ORGANIC PEROXIDE, CONSUMED ALL OF THE FREIGHT IN THE PITT OHIO UNIT.  THE FOUR CARTONS OF ORGANIC PEROXIDE WERE THROWN OUT OF THE REAR OF THE UNIT DURING IMPACT.  THESE UNITS DID NOT LEAK AND ONLY HAD THE OUTSIDE CARTON DAMPENED BY WATER.  THESE FOUR CARTONS WERE PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM FOR RETURN BACK TO SHIPPER.  AT THE TIME OF THE INITIAL CALL TO MYSELF, I CONTACTED CHEMTREC FOR MSDS.  A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE, HMHTTC, AND PERSONNEL FROM OUR LOCAL TERMINAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  ADDITIONAL CALLS WERE PLACED TO PA DEP AND LATER THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  THE EPA AND DOT BOTH CONTACTED US LATER THAT MORNING FOR FOLLOW UP ON SITUATION BUT WERE SATISFIED WITH DECISIONS BEING MADE.  ALL MATERIAL FROM INCIDENT WAS CLEANED UP BY HMHTTC AND IS CURRENTLY AWAITING PROFILING FOR DISPOSAL.  ALTHOUGH ALL THE MATERIALS IN THE UNIT WAS DAMAGED BY THE FIRE, THE LIQUID IN METAL DRUMS FROM ASHLAND AND ICI PAINTS APPEARED TO BE FOR THE MOST PART INTACT.  AT THIS TIME, DEP AND EPA ARE NOT REQUIRING ANY FURTHER DOCUMENTATION ON THE INCIDENT AND ONCE DISPOSAL IS COMPLETE, I SEE NO FURTHER ACTION BEING TAKEN.

column168: During acceptance of shipper loaded and shrink-wrapped skid, it was identified as being too tall to load into a container. Shipment was tendered to Delta as electrical equipment. The FAA has been notified as required by 49 CFR 175.31 and FAA Special Agent Wendy Dent-Henry inspected and released shipment.
column169: Delta was not aware of this situation until the skid was required to be broke down. Delta followed all current U.S. security measures in place prior to transport of this shipment. There were no red flags on this shipment that would have indicated a closer look was necessary. Our agents are trained to identify all Hazard labels and in this case they were hidden from sight.

column168: A IBC containing Compound PS-2 LF was being pumped from an IBC to a tank at the facility.  After the pumping was complete and the hose was detached from the IBC the operator was brining the hose back to the IBC to clean out any excess material.  Approximately 2 feet from the IBC the hose ruptured and sprayed a small amount of material on his thighs.  The hole was less than a quarter inch diameter.  The hose was placed back into the IBC to flush the material out and contain any further release.  He was immediately washed in a safety shower but send to ER for observation.  The spill was immediately contained (wihtin seconds), small amounts that were released (approximately 2 gallons) were neutralized and cleaned up immediately.
column169: THe hose is actually what caused the release.  We currently inspect the hose prior to each use and replaced it as needed.  We have now implemented an annual replacement of the hose.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While at the Alliance Airlines facility located at JFK Airport in Jamaica, New York, one carton, containing one, fifty kilogram fiber drum was discovered punctured.  Approximately, one teaspoon of product released onto the pallet.  The release was due to a puncture by a forklift.  H.M.H.T.T.C. of Parsippany, New Jersey responded to the scene to perform the cleanup.  H.M.H.T.T.C. placed the damaged drum into one, fifty-five gallon overpack drum.  The cleanup materials were placed into one, thirty gallon fiber recovery drum.  H.M.H.T.T.C. coordinated disposal of all waste generated.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and due to a puncture by a forklift, Alliance Airlines will continue standard safety handling procedures to prevent recurrence.

column168: Driver picked up trailer from Tankwash and proceeded to shipper. Operator pulled valve to check for cleanliness when product spilled out. Shipper cleaned up and disposed of product.  Tankwash had not cleaned trailer.

The driver failed to close the venting system on the top of the cargo tank. When the driver departed the loading facility product was released through the vent on the top of the trailer causing product to run down the sides of the trailer. The driver noticed product on the sides of the trailer and immediately stopped. CTL sent out a clean up crew and mechanic to ckeck the vent on the top of the trailer. The harden product was chipped up off the asphalt surface. The product was contained on the trailer and an asphalt surface.
column169: The driver was counseled on proper securement procedures and awarness.

column168: A TRAILER, A-11 WAS BEING LOADED WITH 27% AQUA AMMONIA AT THE AIR PRODUCTS FACILITY IN TAMAQUA, PENNSYLVANIA.  A 2" HOSE WAS CONNECTED TO THE SUCTION SIDE OF THE PUMP THAT IS AFFIXED TO THE TRAILER; AND THE PRODUCT TRANSFER WAS IN PROGRESS.  THE DISCHARGE SIDE OF THE PUMP IS PIPED IN TWO DIRECTIONS.  ONE WAY IT IS PIPED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WHERE AN INTERNAL VALVE WAS OPEN TO ALLOW PRODUCT INTO THE TRAILER.  THE OTHER DIRECTION THAT PRODUCT CAN MOVE IS TO THE LOCATION WHERE A HOSE WOULD BE CONNECTED TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER WITH A TRANSFER HOSE.  THIS PORT WAS NOT BEING USED AT THE TIME OF THIS INCIDENT AND WAS CAPPED OFF WITH THE APPROPRIATE DEVICE.  THIS 2" CAP WAS EITHER NOT PROPERLY SECURED OR VIBRATED OPEN DURING THIS LOADING PROCEDURE.  THE CAP OPENED AND ALLOWED PRODUCT TO SPILL TO THE GROUND IN A CONTAINED AREA.  THE DRIVER THAT WAS MONITORING THE LOADING OPERATION SHUT DOWN THE PUMP AND VALVE IMMEDIATELY (<10 SECONDS).  A TOTAL OF EIGHT GALLONS SPILLED INTO THE CONTAINED AREA, AND WAS PROPERLY REMOVED.
column169: THE STEPS THAT WE WILL TAKEN TO PREVENT ANY RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT WILL BE: 1- INSTALL A 2" BLOCK VALVE PRIOR TO THE LOCATION OF THE CAP, JUST DOWN STREAM OF THE DISCHARGE SIDE OF THE PUMP.  2- SECURE THE CAPS LOCKING DEVISE WITH A SAFETY STRAP THAT WILL PREVENT THE CAP FROM VIBRATING OPEN.  3-REVIEW THE SAFE OPERATING PROCEDURE WITH ALL PERSONNEL THAT WILL BE PERFORMING THIS PROCEDURE.

column168: MIS-CALCULATION ON RETAIN IN TANK.  SYSTEM SHUT-DOWN ACTIVATED AND SHUT LOADING RACK DOWN.  SMALL AMOUNT OF FUEL ENTERED THE RECOVERY SYSTEM ON THE TRUCK.  AS TRUCK LEFT THE LOAD RACK THE FUEL MIGRATED AND SPILLED OUT OF THE OPENING ON THE RECOVERY SYSTEM.  FUEL WAS "MOPPED" UP WITH ABSORBANT PADS TOTAL TIME OF RELEASE AND MOP-UP LESS THAN 2 MINUTES.
column169: RE-EDUCATION OF TRUCK & LOADING RACK PROCEDURES WITH USE MORE OF A "CUSHION" IN CALCULATION OF RETAIN AND CAPACITY OF TANK - IE - 700 GALLON TANK, ASSUMED 200 GALLON RETAIN, LEAVES 500 GALLONS, WILL LOAD 450 GALLONS, 50 GALLON CUSHION.

TRUCK CAME BACK ONTO ROADWAY BUT TRAILER SLID DOWN SOFT EMBANKMENT WHICH PULLED THE TRUCK SIDEWAYS CAUSING BOTH UNITS TO ROLL OVER.  TRAILER ON DIRT-GRASSY WIDE FLAT SHOULDER.  TRUCK PARTIALLY ON SHOULDER & PARTIALLY IN ROADWAY.  BOTH CAME TO REST ON LEFT SIDE.  TRUCK TANK DID NOT LEAK BUT TRAILER TANK LEAK FROM SEVERAL FRACTURES TO TANK CAUSED BY THE ROLLOVER.  NO INJURIES AND NO OTHER VEHICLES INVOLVED.  HWY IS VERY RURAL WITH LIGHT TRAFFIC.  3,098 GALLONS (APPROX.) SPILLED ON GRASSY FLAT SHOULDER (CLEAR DIESEL) 2,029 GALLONS WAS PUMPED OFF GROUND INTO CONTAINERS & TAKEN TO A FACILITY (INDUSTRIAL OIL) FOR DISPOSAL.  1,069 GALLONS WAS REMOVED OUT OF CONTAMINATED SOIL.  APPROX. 225 YRDS OF SOIL.  OREGON DEQ SUPERVISED REMOVAL & CLEAN DIRT DROVE IT BACK INTO SITE.  SOIL SAMPLES WERE TAKEN PRIOR TO CLEAN DIRT BEING PUT IN.

column168: ON MAY 27, 2005, A TRACTOR-TRAILER BEING WEIGHTED AND INSPECTED AT A WEIFHT STATION HAD RELEASED PHOSPHORIC ACID FROM THE TRIALER ONTO THE WEIGHT STATIONS CONCRETE BELOW.  APPROXIMATELY 1/4 OF A GALLON WAS RELEASED AT THE WEIGHT STATIONM AND <10 GALLONS WERE IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. AT APPROXIMATELY 8:55 P.M. CDT, KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES CONTACTED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP.  BASED ON THE INFORMATION PROVIDED BY KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES AND THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR TRAILER, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER DISPATCHED A CREW FROM D&H PUMP SERVICES (D&H) TO PERFORM THE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  THE CREW FROM D&H ARRIVED ON-SITE TO ASSESS THE SCOPE OF THE RELEASE.  THE TRACTOR TRAILER HAD NOT BEEN MOVED FROM THE INTIAL LOCATION AT THE TRAILER DOORS REMAINED LOCKED.  DUE TO THE RANGE OF CHEMICALS BEING TRANSPORTED IN THE TRAILER THE CREW DONNED THE PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT (PPE) BEFORE ENTERING THE TRAILER.  ONCE THE TRAILER DOORS WERE OPENED AND THE CREW ENTERED THE TRAILER, IT WAS THEN THAT THE CREW LEARNED THAT THE RELEASED CHEMICAL WAS METHANOL SULFURIC ACID.  THE RELEASE OF THE ACID HAD SPREAD THROUGHOUT THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER, AND THE TRAILER WOULD HAVE TO BE UNLOADED.  THE WEIGHT STATION WOULD NOT PERMIT THE CLEAN UP ACTIONS TO BE PERFORMED ON THE TRAILER AT THEIR FACILITY.  WITH APPROVAL FROM KLLM TRANSPORTATION SERVICES AND THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER THE D&H CREW ASSISTED THE DRIVER AND HIS VEHCILE TO THEIR SHOP TO PERFORM THE REMEDIATION OF THE TRAILER.  BEFORE THE TRANSPORT WAS MADE THE CREW REMEDIATED THE CONCRETE OF THE WEIGHT STATION BY NEUTRALIZING THE SOLUTION AND APPLYING ABSORBENT MATERIALS.  THOSE MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  THE TRAILER WAS THEN STABILIZED FOR TRANSPORT.  THE TRAILER WAS REMEDIATED AT D&H FACILITY, AND THE DRIVER RETURNED TO THE ROAD THE FOLLOWING AFTERNOON.

column168: One cylinder was found leaking on the inbound trailer. The cylinder was leaking from a defective valve. column168: DRIVER ENTERED TRL WITH LIFT.  PUT BLADES INTO SKID AND LIFTED SKID.  BLADES CAME UP THEN BOTTOM OF SKID AND PUNCTURED 1 55 GALLON DRUM ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  TOTAL LOSS OF PRODUCT MOST OF WHICH LEAKED INTO THE TRL.  CLEARED THE AREA AND CALLED SAFETY PERSONNEL.  PUT OIL DRY ON THE PRODUCT ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  PRODUCT LEAKED FROM NOSE INTO A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DRUM.  PUT OIL DRY ON THE GROUND IN FRONT & THE REAR OF THE TRL TO STOP ABSORB THE PRODUCT RELEASED ON THE GROUND OUTSIDE THE TRL, CLEAN UP CREW ARRIVED AND CLEAND UP SPILL AND TRAILER AND AREA UNDER AND AROUND TRL.  REMOVED DAMAGED DRUM.

column168: DURING INSPECTION PRIOR TO LOADING THE FREIGHT ON ULDS, LABELS WERE NOTICED COVERING PRERPINTED CALSS 9 LABELS AND THE UN 3268 NUMBER.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION ONE BOX WAS NOTICED TO HAVE VISIBLE CLASS 9 LABELS.  AT THAT POINT LOADING OF THE SHIPMENT WAS HALTED AND STHE SHIPMENT WAS SEGREGATED.  LOGISTICS AND DEWEY BETHEL WERE NOTIFIED.  THE FREIGHT WAS LOCKED UP AND HELD FOR FURTHER INSPECTION THE FOLLOWING DAY.  AT APPROX 1000 TSA INSPECTOR DAVID BROADNAX ARRIVED AT OUR WAREHOUSE, SAYING THAT ANGELICA FROM TEAM AIR HAD NOTIFIED HIM OF THE INCIDENT.  HE OPENED AND INSPECTED AND PHOTOGRAPHED THE CONTENTS OF ALL BOXES, SIX OF THE SEVEN BOXES HAD EXPENDED AIRBAGS, THE SEVENTH BOX WHICH WAS ONT HE BOTTOM ROW HAD VISIBLE UNCOVERED CALSS 9 LABELS AND CONTAINED WHAT APPEARED TO BE LIVE AIRBAG MODULES.

column168: DRAYMAN REPORTED INTERMODAL CONTAINER NCHU 283044 IN BNSF'S INTERMODAL PARKING LOT LEAKING AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE.  NCHU 283044 WAS TAKEN TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE BNSF RESPONDER AND SHIPPER CONTRACT RESPONDERS NOTED AIR BAGS USED AS BRACING (WHICH IS NOT ACCEPTABLE AND INSUFFICIENT FOR LOADS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS) IN THIS MIXED LOAD OF VARIOUS PACKAGE TYPES.  ONE METAL CAGED POLY TOTE WAS FOUND LEAKING.  APPARENTLY, DRUMS ADJACENT TO THIS TOTE SHIFTED IN TRANSIT AND DAMAGED THE TOTES OUTER CAGE, COLLAPSING THE CAGE INTO THE POLY TOTE.  THE TOTE WAS CUT BY THE DAMAGED CAGE AND RELEASED PRODUCT.  THE REMINING PRODUCT IN THE TOTE WAS TRANSFERRED INTO RECOVERY DRUMS.  THE SPILLAGE INSIDE CONTAINER WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP.  ALL LADING, INCLUDING THE RECOVERY DRUMS AND THE EMPTY DAMAGED TOTE WERE RETURNED INTO NCHU 283044 AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: AT 0800 HOURS ON MONDAY, MAY 16TH TANK CAR DODX14271 WAS OBSERVED BY A CSX MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEE LEAKING PRODUCT OUT OF BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE AREA AROUND THE RAIL CAR WAS ISOLATED AND HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MANAGER HOPES WAS CONTACTED TO SECURE CONTAINER.  INVESTIGATION REVEALS THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER PREPARATION FOR SHIPMENT.  THE JAMESBURY WAFERSPHERE VALVE HANDLE WAS NOT PINNED IN THE CLOSED POSITION AS REQUIRED.  THE VALVE WAS OPEN DURING TRANSIT AND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS FOUND LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  THE COMBINATION OF THESE ERRORS ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY FOUR (4) GALLONS OF AVIATION FUEL.  THE PRIMARY AND SECONDARY CLOSURES WERE PROPERLY SECURED AND A CABLE SEAL WAS APPLIED TO THE VALVE HANDLE RETAINING PIN.  THE RELEASE WAS CLEANED UP UTILIZING SORBANT MATERIAL.  AS ADDITIONAL INFORMATION, SEVEN (7) OF EIGHT (8) MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE FOUND LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  THE CAR WAS PROPERLY SECURED THEN RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: A 4-COMPARTMENT TRAILER WAS IN ROUTE TO LOUISVILLE, KY.  IN COMPARTMENT #1 WAS ISOPAR L-PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID 1268, PGIII.  COMPARTMENT #2 & 3 CONTAINED EXXAL 13 (TRIDECYL ALCOHOL) & COMPARTMENT #4 CONTAINED EXXSOL D 80 FLUID.  A ROLLOVER ACCIDENT OCCURRED ON I-65 OUTSIDE OF LEBANON, INDIANA.  AS OUR DRIVER APPROACHED MILE-MARKER #138 A DEER RAN OUT IN FRONT OF THE TRACTOR.  THE DRIVER SWERVED TO AVOID THE DEER BUT WOUND UP HITTING IT.  (THE BODY OF THE DEER WAS RECOVERED AT THE SCENE BY THE INDIANA STATE POLICE).  AS A RESULT OF THIS SUDDEN MOVEMENT ALONG WITH THE SURGE OF THE PRODUCT THE TRAILER ROLLED OVER.  WHEN IT STOPPED IT RESTED IN THE CENTER OF I-65.  BOTH LANES OF THE HIGHWAY WERE SHUT DOWN BECAUSE A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS INVOLVED..  SHORTLY THEREAFTER ONE DIRECTION WAS RE-OPENED.  WHEN THE TRAILER ROLLED OVER, THE VENTS ON COMPARTMENT #1 WERE SEVERELY DAMAGED AND ISOPAR L LEAKED OUT OF COMPARTMENT #1.  SPILL RECOVERY OF INDIANA WAS CALLED INTO CLEAN-UP THE SPILL AND ZOREYS RECOVERY TOWED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER AWAY FROM THE SCENE.
column169: THIS ACCIDENT OCCURRED BECAUSE A DEER RAN OUT IN FRONT OF OUR TRAILER.  WHILE IT IS IMPOSSIBLE TO STOP THIS FROM REOCCURRING LANGER TRANSPORT IS LOOKING INTO PURCHASING DEER WHISTLES AND MOUNTING THEM ON OUR TRACTORS.  THE SPILL OCCURRED BECAUSE THE VENTS WERE DAMAGED IN THE ROLLOVER.  THE ACTUAL STRUCTURE AND INTEGRITY OF THE TRAILER WERE IN TACT DESPITE ROLLING OVER AT 55 MILES PER HOUR.  AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING WE WILL DISCUSS THIS EVENT AND EDUCATE OUR DRIVERS ON WHAT CAUSES ROLLOVERS.  TOPICS WILL INCLUDE CENTRIFUGAL FORCE, LOAD SHIFT, SUDDEN MANEUVERS, AND INATTENTIVE DRIVING.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While unloading at the consignee's location two leaking five gallon metal pails were discovered inside the trailer. column42: PHOSPHORUS PENTASULFIDE, FREE FROM YELLOW OR WHITE PHOSPHORUS
column168: ON 05/12/05 AT 0730 HRS., Q24710 WAS HEADING SOUTH TOWARDS LOUISVILLEM KY., WHEN THE TRAIN HAD AN EMERGENCY APPLICATION.  AFTER INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE 32 THRU THE 42 CARS WERE DERAILED IN A GENERAL PILE UP.  THE 37TH CAR, COVERED HOPPER, WAS UTLX 800000, CARRYING PHOSPHORUS PENTASULFIDE.  WHEN THE LOCAL POLICE FOUND THAT THE CAR WAS CARRYING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, THEY DECIDED TO CLOSE THE ROAD SINCE THE CAR ENDED NEXT TO RT. #60.  THIS WAS AT 0745 HRS.  AT 0900 HRS., IT WAS REPORTED THAT SOMEONE SMELLED AN ODOR LIKE ROTTEN EGGS, A SMELL THAT IS EMITTED FROM PHOSPHORUS PENTASULFIDE.  IT WAS THEN DECIDED TO EVACUATE ONE HALF MILE OF THE DERAILMENT SCENE.  THE LOCAL MARSHALL, JEFF THOMAS, ESTIMATED THAT 60 HOMES AND ONE BUSINESS WERE EFFECTED FROM 0900 HRS. UNTIL 1431 HRS. TO INCLUDE 200 PEOPLE AND 2 EMPLOYEES.  AT 1400 HRS., CSXT MET WITH SALEM, IN., FIRE DEPARTMENT.  IT WAS DISCUSSED THAT AFTER AIR MONITORING FROM CTEH AND SUMMIT ENVIRONMENTAL, THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF ANY PRODUCT INTO THE AIR ATMOSPHERE.  DAMAGE ASSESSMENT DONE BY CSXT, SHOWED THERE WAS NO DANGER THAT THE CAR WOULD RUPTURE AND SPILL ANY PRODUCT ONTO THE GROUND.  THE EVACUATION WAS LIFTED AT 1413 HRS. AND RERAILING OPERATIONS BEGAN.  STATE HIGHWAY RT. #60 REMAINED CLOSED UNTIL 0900 HRS. THE NEXT DAY, TO ALLOW RAIL ROAD CONTRACTORS TO CLEAN THE DERAILMENT.

THE TRAINMASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN THOMASVILLE, GA REPORTED THAT TANK CAR, ACFX 73052, LOAD FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS NOS (CRUDE SULFATE TURPENTINE), HAD A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM IT.  HE ADVISED THAT HE COULD NOT SEE ANY EVIDENCE OF ANY LIQUID RELEASE FROM THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER, INTERNATIONAL PAPER WAS NOTIFIED.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CAR AND MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE FOLLOWING DEFECTS; (1) ALL THE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT, (2) THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS FOLDED INSIDE THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND WAS NOT MAKING A SEAL, AND (3) THE LIQUID LINE VALVE PLUG WAS NOT INSTALLED.  THE CONTRACTOR STRAIGHTENED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET, CLOSED AND SECURED THE MANWAY COVER AND INSTALLED THE LIQUID VALVE PLUG.  THE ODOR THEN WENT AWAY.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  INTERNATIONAL PAPER WAS ADVISED OF THE DEFECTS FOUND ON THE CAR.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While loading at the BAX Global Inc. facility, a release was discovered on the dock.  Apparently, one cardboard carton, which contained one steel drum, had been punctured, and two(2) others were damaged, yet not leaking.  It appeared the puncture occurred at the loading facility (Salt Lake City).  The freight was shrinkwrapped on a pallet of 15 cardboard cartons.  Approximately 1 tablespoon had been released upon moving the freight, and was unrecoverable due to wind blowing the product from the dock.  The entire shrinkwrapped pallet was covered in plastic and isolated, pending further action.  Advanced Cleanup Technologies of Wilmington, California was dispatched to assist in overpacking the damaged carton, and coordinating disposal per local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.  The remainder of the shipment will be forwarded onto the consignee.
column169: BAX Global Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines in regard to loading/offloading and handling of freight.

column168: FORK LIFT DRIVER PUTTING A PALLET INTO TRAILER.  THE 5 GAL HM CONTAINER WAS IMPROPERLY SECURED ON ANOTHER PALLET.  THE SHAKING OF THE TRAILER CAUSED BY FORKLIFT ENTERING TRAILER CAUSED THE 5 GAL PAIL TO FALL TO THE FLOOR.  BENDING THE SIDE OF THE PAIL AND CAUSING THE LID TO COME OFF.  THE WHOLE CONTENTS OF THE 5 GAL PAIL WERE SPILLED OUT.  FORKLIFT DRIVER CONTACTED THE SUPERVISOR WHEN HE NOTICED THE SPILL. column168: A PALLET OF PAINT AND PAINT-RELATED MATERIAL HAD BEEN PUSHED INTO ANOTHER SHIPMENT.  THIS WAS CAUSED BY PUSHING OTHER SHIPMENTS, ALSO ON PALLETS, INTO THE TRAILER, PROBABLY WITH A FORKLIFT.  THE PALLET OF PAINT WAS NOT UNIFORM - ONE BOX STUCK OUT ON ONE SIDE.  THIS BOX WAS COMPRESSED AGAINST THE SHIPMENT IN FRONT OF IT.  THE COMPRESSION CAUSED A CAN OF BLACK FLUID, UPSIDE DOWN IN THE REPACKED CASE, TO POP OPEN.  THE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT, MOSTLY ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  AFTER THE TRAILER WAS EMPTIED, WE MOVED IT OUT INTO THE YARD TO AIR OUT AND DRY.  WE TOOK THE PALLET APART, ISOLATED THE DAMAGED BOX, AND SENT THE REST OF THIS SHIPMENT OUT FOR DELIVERY.
column169: 1.  PROVIDE FEEDBACK TO THE FEDEX FREIGHT SERVICE CENTER THAT LOADED THE FREIGHT.  (THAT HAD BEEN DONE.)  2.  ENCOURAGE BUSINESSES THAT SHIP PAINT TO LOAD IT RIGHT-SIDE UP.

column168: A WAREHOUSE WORKER WAS PICKING PRODUCTS FROM STORAGE WITH A DUAL "PARROT BEAK" DRUM PICKER.  THE DRUM PICKER GRABS THE RIM OF THE DRUM TO MOVE TO DESTINATION.  THE PARROT BEAK FAILED TO GRAB THE DRUM CORRECTLY BECAUSE OF AN INDENT ON THE DRUM CAUSING THE DRUM TO DROP FROM THE PICKER (A FEW INCHES).  WHEN THE DRUM HIT THE GROUND, THE BUNG LOCATED ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM POPPED OFF BECAUSE IT WAS NOT FITTED PROPERLY.  THE FALL TO THE FLOOR CAUSED THE DRUM TO TEETER AND DROP SIDEWAYS AND BECAUSE THERE WAS NO SEAL ON THE DRUM SEVERAL GALLONS (ABOUT 5) LEAKED ON THE FLOOR.  THE IN-HOUSE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM CONTAINED THE LIQUID ACCORDING TO THE MSDS AND THE SPILL WAS OVERPACKED AND SENT BACK TO ORIGINAL CUSTOMER THAT PROVED THE PRODUCT.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTIONS INCLUDE LOOKING INTO FAILURE OF THE DRUM PICKER AND HAVE MAINTENANCE DONE.  ALSO HAVING CUSTOMER RE-TRAIN EMPLOYEES ON PROPER CAPPING FUNCTIONS AND ESTABLISH A QUALITY CONTROL PROCESS.  TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING WE WILL HAVE MAINTENANCE DONE MONTHLY ON DRUM PICKERS AND WILL REQUIRE CUSTOMER TO PROVIDE A QUALITY CONTROL CHECKLIST ON CAPS AND BUNGS PERIODICALLY.

column168: THE TRAINMASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN CHARLESTON, WV REPORTED THAT HIS YARD CREW REPORTED A STRONG ODOR IN THE YARD AROUND TRACKS 9 AND 10.  THE TRAINMASTER CONTACTED THE DOW CHEMICAL ER TEAM AND REQUESTED THEY RESPOND TO CHECK CARS IN THE YARD.  THE DOW TEAM DISCOVERED TANK CAR, ETCX 22029, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, ACETALDEHYDE, TO BE HISSING AROUND ONE OF THE HEX BOLTS THAT ATTACHS THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK.  THEY TIGHTENED THE HEX BOLT AND ALMOST STOPPPED THE VAPOR LEAK, BUT THEY COULD STILL HEAR A SLIGHT HISSING SOUND FROM AROUND THE BOLT.  THE DOW TEAM INDICATED THAT THE RESIDUE CAR HAD A NITROGEN BLANKET ON IT AND WAS UNDER SOME PRESSURE.  THEY REQUESTED TO HAVE THE CAR MOVED BACK TO THEIR FACILITY SO THEY COULD DRAW ALL PRESSURE AND ALL VAPORS OFF OF THE CAR SO THEY COULD COMPLETE THEIR REPAIRS.  THE CAR WAS MOVED A SHORT DISTANCE BACK TO THE UNION CARBIDE (DOW) FACILITY SO THEY COULD REDUCE THE PRESSURE AND DRAW OFF THE VAPORS.

CONTAINER SCMU 200162, WHILE IN TRANSIT ON TRAIN Q12024, WAS SEEN VENTING WHITE PUFFS OF SMOKE BY RAIL PERSONNEL.  LOCAL FIRE AND PD WERE NOTIFIED, WHO IN TURN EVACUATED TWO LOCAL BUSINESSES.  ALSO EFFECTED WERE 3 HOTELS IN THE AREA, AT WHICH OCCUPANTS WERE NOTIFIED TO SHELTER IN PLACE.  THE CONTAINER WAS SHIPPED BY HORIZON LINES, LLC, UNDER CONTRACT BY LINDE GAS CO. 159 RESIDUE CYLINDERS OF ANHYDROUS HCL WERE IN THE CONTAINER.  LINDE GAS AND SUNPRO SERVICES WERE CONTRACTED TO REMEDIATE.  UPON OPENING THE CONTAINER, THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING EVIDENT.  ON 15 OF THE CYLINDERS, STAINING WAS PRESENT, EVIDENCE OF VAPOR ESCAPING AND MIXING WITH ATMOSPHERIC MOISTURE TO FORM HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  ALL CYLINDERS WERE REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER, DECONTAMINATED, AND INSPECTED.  THE LEAKING CYLINDERS WERE FOUND TO HAVE VAPOR CAPS NOT WRENCH TIGHT, AS WELL AS VALVES THAT WERE NOT FULLY CLOSED.  AFTER REPACKING THE CONTAINER, BLOCKING WAS INSTALLED.  CYLINDERS FOUND LEAKING WERE: TW04-732882, 732909, 732854, 732861, AND 732870.  THE OTHER 10 CYLINDERS HAD LABELS OBSCURING THE SERAL NUMBERS, NOT ABLE TO RECORD.

THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.  SPILLAGE WAS ON COMPANY PROPERTY ONLY (NO PUBLIC ROADWAYS OR PUBLIC AREAS.)  THERE WERE NO ENVIRONMENTAL RELEASES TO AIR, WATER OR LAND, OTHER THAN THE FACILITY CONCRETE AND ASPHALT AREAS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE TO HUMAN HEALTH.  SPILLAGE OCCURRED DUE TO IMPROPERLY SEATED PAIL GASKET AS WELL AS INTERNAL CONTAINER RUPTURE (CRACKED LID).  ALL METALLIC MERCURY WAS CLEANED-UP WITHIN 36 HRS. OF THE RELEASE.
column169: -ADDITIONAL TRAINING FOR CUSTOMER ON BEST METHODS OF PACKAGING LIQUID MERCURY.  - ADDITIONAL TRAINING FOR SHIPPING 1 RECEIVING PERSONNEL ON PROPER METHODS OF CONTAINER INSPECTIONS (PROPER CLOSURE, INSPECTION FOR LEAKS, ETC.)  - ADDITIONAL OVERPACKING METHODS TO BE IMPLEMENTED FOR CONTAINERS OF LIQUID MERCURY.

column168: AMMONIA TANK STORED IN DIKE HAD JUST BEEN FILLED. TANK FAILURE OCCURRED AT THE BOTTOM OF TANK DUE TO HEAD PRESSURE FROM PRODUCT. PRODUCT SPILLED INTO DIKE AREA. BRIAN ZIEGLER TO RECOVER SPILLED PRODUCT INTO VENDOR'S TRUCK, BEGAN RECOVERY. GEORGE ZOLOVICK AND LEPC WERE CONTACTED. COMPLETED RECOVERY FROM DIKE. DURING RECOVERY, FOUND LEAK IN DIKE. USED SOIL TO CREATE DAM TO CONTAIN PRODUCT LEAKING FROM DIKE. RECOVERED MATERIAL WAS TRANSPORTED TO ROYSTER-CLARK IN MASSEY, MD. PRODUCT THAT LEAKED FROM DIKE WAS DILUTED WITH WATER UNDER ADVISEMENT OF MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT (MDE). MDE SUGGESTED THAT AMMONIA WOULD VOLATIZE AND NO CLEANUP WOULD BE NECESSARY.    DURING THE PROCESS OF RECOVERING THE MATERIAL THAT LEAKED FROM THE DIKE, IT WAS NECESSARY TO CLOSE MARYLAND STATE ROUTES 165 AND 136 WHICH SURROUND THE PLANT FOR 1 HOUR AND 48 MINUTES.    MDE INCIDENT NUMBER: 51220051145
column169: STORAGE TANK WILL BE REPLACED WITH ONE CURRENTLY OWNED BY ROYSTER-CLARK AT ANOTHER LOCATION. THE DIKE WILL BE REPAIRED.

column168: EMPLOYEE WAS DELIVERING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WAGON TO A FIELD ON WADESBORO RD. (HWY 1949).  AS HE APPROACHED AN INTERSECTION AND APPLIED THE BRAKES, THE WAGON RAN OFF THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD, STRUCK A DRIVEWAY CULVERT, BLEW OUT A TIRE, AND OVERTURNED IN THE ROAD DITCH.  ONE OF THE VALVES BECAME SLIGHTLY OPEN DURING THE ROLLOVER AND CAUSED A VERY SMALL LEAK.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE LOCATION (HARDIN) BY RADIO AND THE MANAGER AND CREW WENT TO THE SCENE.  A NEIGHBOR PHONED 911.  THE MARSHALL CO. EMERGENCY MGMT. DIRECTOR, THE BREWERS FIRE DEPT. AND THE MARSHALL CO SHERIFF'S DEPT ALL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE FIRE DEPT. SPRAYED A SMALL AMOUNT OF WATER ON THE TANK WHILE ROYSTER-CLARK ASSOCIATES USED A LOADER TO RECOVER THE TANK FROM THE DITCH.  THE EMA ASKED THE RESIDENTS OF THE WESTERFIELD HOUSE TO MOVE AWAY FROM THE SCENE WHILE THE TANK WAS BEING RECOVERED AND THEY SAID THEY WOULD LEAVE THE HOUSE.  THE TANK WAS SET UP AND THE VALVE CLOSED.  THE TIRE AND WHEEL WERE REPLACED AND THE WAGON PULLED BACK TO THE ROYSTER-CLARK FACILITY IN HARDIN.  THE TANK WAS RE-WEIGHED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS NO LOSS.  THE CONCRETE DRIVEWAY CULVERT BELONGING THE COREY WESTERFIELD WAS DAMAGED DURING THE IMPACT.  SOME DAMAGE WAS REPORTED TO THE LAWN ADJACENT TO THE DITCHBANK.
column169: THIS DRIVER AND ALL OTHERS WILL BE RETRAINED ON PROPER TOWING PROCEDURES WHEN TRANSPORTING NURSE WAGONS.

column168: A BNSF PASSING TRAIN CREW REPORTED ODOR AND VAPOR EMANATING FROM UTLX 11209 THAT WAS ENTRAINED IN A PARKED UNATTENDED TRAIN IN THE CATALE (OK) STATION SIDING NEAR CHELSEA, OK.  BNSF RESPONDERS REPORTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE SUMP AREA AND PLACED A RECEPTACLE UNDER THIS TANK CAR TO CAPTURE LEAKAGE.  ASSUMING THE INTERNAL LINER FAILURE THAT RESULTED IN A CORROSION HOLE BREACH IN THE TANK SHELL, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER PRODUCT INTO ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR.  TRANSFER WAS ACCOMPLISHED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT BY 1030 HRS. CDT, 5/29/05 BY BNSF CONTRACTORS ASSISTED BY CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVES.   AFTERWARDS SODA ASH WATER WERE INTRODUCED INSIDE UTLX 11209 TO NEUTRALIZE RESIDUAL PRODUCT INSIDE TANK CAR.  LATER, THE NEUTRALIZED MIXTURE WAS PUMPED INTO A LIQUID VACCUM TRUCK FOR APPROPRIATE DISPOSAL.  A FRA MOVEMENT ARRPOVAL (FRA-05060160) WAS RECEIVED TO DIRECTLY MOVE UTLX 11209 TO A DESIGNATED REPAIR FACILITY.  ANOTHER BNSF CONTRACTOR NEUTRALIZED ALL GROUND SPILLAGE (IMPACTED BALLAST AND SURFACE SOIL) WITH SODA ASH.  LOCAL F.D. EVACUATED ONE NEARBY HOUSEHOLD (ONE PERSON) FOR APPROXIMATELY 2 1/2 HOURS DURING THE INITIAL PHASE OF THIS INCIDENT.  NEARBY COUNTY ROAD 429 WAS ALSO CLOSED DURING THIS SAME TIME PERIOD.

GINGER CARTER OF KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OPERATIONS.  THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER CONTACTED THE DRIVER TO GAIN ADDITIONAL INFORMATION ABOUT THE RELEASE.  BASED ON AVAILABLE INFORMATION, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER DISPATCHED A CREW FROM ENVIRO-CLEAN SERVICES (CES) IN OKLAHOMA CITY, OKLAHOMA TO ASSESS THE RELEASE AND INITIATE ACTIONS.  THE CREW FROM ECS ARRIVED ONSITE, REVIEWED THE SHIPPING DOCUMENTATION AND ENTERED THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, THE CREW OBSERVED ONE (1) PUNCTURED 55-GALLON DRUM OF PHOSPHORIC ACID.  ECS PERSONNEL REMOVED AND OVER PACKED THE LEAKING DRUM.  THE TRAILER FLOOR AND ASPHALT PARKING LOT WERE THEN NEUTRALIZED BY SODA ASH.  THE SPENT SODA ASH WAS COLLECTED, PLACED INTO A 55-DRUM AND COLLECTED FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: THE PERSONNEL AT THE CFI FACILITY WERE UNLOADING THE TRAILER WHEN A LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE CREW IMMEDIATELY HALTED THE UNLOADING AND REVIEWED THE BILL OF LADING.  THE LEAK WAS IDENTIFIED AS A CORROSIVE MATERIAL.  THE DOCK PERSONNEL ORDERED EVERYONE IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA TO LEAVE THE VACINITY OF THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER WAS THEN TOWED TO A REMOTE LOCATION OF THE PARKING LOT.  THE CFI TERMINAL MANAGER CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT FOR CLEANUP.  ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT DISPATCHED HULCHER SERVICES TO RESPOND, LOCATED THE LEAKING DRUM, OVERPACK IT, NEUTRALIZE THE FLOOR AND CLEAN UP THE SURROUNDING AREA.  THE HULCHER CREW ENTERED THE TRAILER, LOCATED THE LEAKING DRUM OVERPACKED IT AND BEGAN NEUTRALIZING THE FLOOR.  THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS FROM A PUNCTURE HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE CARGO WAS LOADED INTO THE TRAILER WITH DEAD SPACE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  THE LOAD WAS ALLOWED TO SHIFT FORWARD CAUSING THE DRUMS TO MOVE AROUND ON THE PALLET.  THIS PARTICULAR DRUM WAS ALLOWED TO MOVE FORWARD AND ONTO AN EXPOSED NAIL CAUSING THE HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE DRUM LOST AN ESTIMATED 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.
column169: IN THE FUTURE THE LOADS NEED TO BE PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED TO PREVENT LOAD SHIP AND THE DRUMS NEED TO BE SECURED TO THE PALLETS.

column168: TRIUMVIRATE'S TRACTOR TRAILER WAS FORCED TO MAKE AN ABRUPT STOP ONLY SECONDS AFTER STARTING AWAY FROM A TRAFFIC LIGHT WHERE THE VEHICLE HAD BEEN STOPPED FOR A RED LIGHT.  THE ESTIMATED SPEED THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING AT THE TIME THE BRAKES WERE APPLIED WAS LESS THAN 5 MPH.  AN AUTOMOBILE DRIVING IMMEDIATELY IN FRONT OF OUR TRUCK WAS STRUCK ON ITS REAR BUMPER BY OUR VEHICLE, RESULTING IN A "FENDER BENDER".  AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT, LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT WAS SUMMONED TO THE SCENE.  THE NATURE OF THE SUDDEN STOP CAUSED A SLIGHT SHIFT OF THE LOAD OF WASTE-CONTAINING PACKAGES IN THE VEHICLE TRAILER.  TWO OF THE PACKAGES LOCATED AT THE VERY FRONT (NOSE) OF THE TRAILER, BOTH 5-GALLON (1H1/Y1.8) HIGH DENSITY POLYETHYLENE CONTAINERS, WERE APPARENTLY COMPRESSED SLIGHTLY DUE TO THE SUDDEN MOVEMENT OF ADJACENT CONTAINERS.  THIS COMPRESSION OF THE CONTAINERS RESULTED IN A RELEASE OF MATERIAL FROM BOTH OF THE 5-GALLON CONTAINERS.  THE RELEASE OF THE LIQUIDS WAS DETECTED BY TRIUMVIRATE'S DRIVER AS SHE SPOKE WITH RESPONDING LAW ENFORCEMENT.  BOTH OUR DRIVER AND THE OFFICER NOTICED THAT LIQUIDS WERE DRIPPING ONTO THE HIGHWAY SURFACE FROM THE FLOOR BOARD OF THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  BECAUSE OF THE DRIPPING COMING FROM THE TRAILER, THE LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICER INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVER TO MOVE THE VEHICLE TO ITS ORIGINAL DESTINATION LOCATED NEARBY, WHICH SHE DID AFTER CALLING AHEAD AND GETTING APPROVAL TO DO SO.  ONCE AT THE DESTINATION THE TWO SUSPECTED CONTAINERS WERE IDENTIFIED AND THE INDIVIDUAL CONTENTS DETERMINED.  THE CONTAINERS WERE NOT LEAKING WHEN THEY WERE INSPECTED AT THE DESTINATION AND IT WAS APPARENT THAT ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM EACH CONTAINER.  LATER THAT DAY IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ROUGHLY EIGHT OUNCES OF LIQUID HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM EACH CONTAINER, THE SPECIFIC CONTENTS OF WHICH ARE DESCRIBED ELSEWHERE IN THIS REPORT.  BASED ON THAT RELEASE ESTIMATE, THE CONTAINERS LIKELY ONLY RELEASED CONTENTS AT THE TIME OF IMPACT FOR A SECOND OR TWO, AND STOPPED DOING SO WHEN THE VEHICLE CAME TO A STOPPED.  NEITHER CONTAINER APPEARED DAMAGED IN ANY WAY AND IT IS LIKELY THAT THE RELEASE OCCURRED THROUGH THE SCREW CAP AT THE MOMENT THE TRUCK APPLIED ITS BRAKES.
column169: TRIUMVIRATE BELIEVES THAT THE RELEASE WAS A DIRECT CONSEQUENCE OF THE SUDDEN BRAKING OF OUR VEHICLE AND SUBSEQUENT SHIFTING OF THE CONTAINERS IN QUESTION.  NEVERTHELESS, THERE ARE STEPS THAT WE CAN TAKE TO LESSEN THE LIKELIHOOD OF A FUTURE REPEAT EVENT UNDER SIMILAR CIRCUMSTANCES.  THESE INCLUDE: 1. RE-ENFORCEMENT OF PROPER AND SAFE DRIVING TECHNIQUES.  2.  WHERE NECESSARY, MAKING SURE THAT SHIPPING CONTAINERS ARE STORED AND CLOSED IN A MANNER THAT LIMITS THE RISK OF A SIMILAR RELEASE TO THE EXTENT POSSIBLE.  3.  TRIUMVIRATE IS ALSO INVESTIGATING THE VIABILITY OF INSTALLING SECONDARY CONTAINMENT IN OUR VEHICLES.  4.  TRIUMVIRATE CONSIDERS TAKING DISCIPLINARY ACTION, WITH RE-TRAINING, WHEN IT'S WARRANTED.

column168: GASOLINE SPILLED INTO THE EAST ROAD DITCH OF DYESS AVENUE WHEN THE TRANSPORT OFF AN APPROACH TO THE GOODYEAR TIRE STORE.  THE RAPID CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO THE SITE AND DAKOTA CLAIMS OVERSAW THE INITIAL CONTAINMENT.  DIRT BERMS WERE PLACED IN THE DITCH BOTTOM TO MITIGATE FLOW OF FREE PRODUCT DOWN THE DITCH.  THE OVERTURNED PUP WAS REMOVED FROM THE DITCH WITH A CRANE.  APPROXIMATELY 480 GALLONS REMAINED IN THE TANK AND 3520 GALLONS WERE RELEASED TO THE SURFACE SOILS IN THE DITCH BOTTOM.  AMERICAN ENGINEERING TESTING HAS BEEN RETAINED TO OVERSEE AN INITIAL EXCAVATION AND TRANSPORT TO THE RAPID CITY LANDFILL.  SOIL VAPOR EXTRACTION PIPING WAS PLACED IN THE EXCAVATION FOR REMEDIATION OF IMPACTED SOIL REMAINING BENEATH DYESS AVE. AND UTILITIES ADJACENT TO THE DITCH.
column169: WHILE THE COMPANY HAS AN EXTENSIVE TRAINING POLICY AND ORIENTATION, CIRCUMSTANCES OF MULTIPLE CONSTRUCTION PROJECTS ONGOING IN THAT PARTICULAR AREA PROBABLY CONTRIBUTED TO THIS INCIDENT AND BAD JUDGMENT ON THE PART OF THE DRIVER.

column168: ON MAY 24, 2005 OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING PROPANE DELIVERIES TO OUR RESIDENTIAL AND COMMERCIAL ACCOUNTS.  HE WAS ON RANTZ LANE, WHICH IS A NARROW DIRT MOUNTAIN ROAD, GOING UP THE MOUNTAIN TO MAKE A DELIVERY TO A COMMERCIAL DRILLING ACCOUNT.  HIS RIGHT FRONT TIRE GOT INTO THE SOFT SHOULDER, CAUSING THE TRUCK TO ROLLOVER, DOWN THE HILL TO THE PASSENGER SIDE.  THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER ABOUT 100 DEGREES WHEN THE TRUCK CAB CAME TO REST AGAINST A TREE, WHICH CRUSHED THE TOP OF THE CAB ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE, KILLING THE DRIVER.  AS INDICATED EARLIER, THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT, NOR WAS THERE ANY STRUCTURAL DAMAGE TO THE CARGO TANK OR THE LADING RETENTION SYSTEM.

column168: ON MAY 6, 2005 AT APPROXIMATELY 13:20 HOURS, A RAILWAY TANK CAR PPGX 3452, LOADED WITH SODIUM HYDROXIDE, CORROSIVE, UN1824 PG II, WAS REPORTED LEAKING AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) BOSSIER CITY, LOUISIANA YARD.  THE TANK CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE FLANGE WHERE THE VALVE BOLTS TO THE TANK CAR SHELL. T HE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE RESPONDED TO THE SITE TIGHTENING THE BOLTS ON THE FLANGE FITTING AND CORRECTING THE RELEASE..  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, NO DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT, CAR WAS RELEASED TO ITS DESTINATION.
column169: ON THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR), SHIPPERS ARE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF ALL HAZMAT RELEASES.  FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE OR CLOSURE DEFECTS), WHERE POSSIBLE, SHIPPERS ARE REQUESTED TO RESPOND, REPAIR, AND REMEDIATE.  BY IMMEDIATELY INVOLVING THE SHIPPER, IN-DEPTH KNOWLEDGE OF THE RELEASE CAUSE IS GAINED BY THE SAME ORGANIZATION THAT CAN IMPLEMENT PROCESS CHANGES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.  AFTER EACH RELEASE INCIDENT, KCSR PROVIDES OUTREACH TO THE SHIPPER TO HELP INVESTIGATE ROOT-CAUSE FACTORS FOR CORRECTION.  FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELATED RELEASES, THE SHIPPER SHOULD BE CONTACTED DIRECTLY FOR DETAILS ASSOCIATED WITH ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

Oil transport operator Sidney Hargrave delivered a load of diesel fuel to the BAP ANTO FAGASTA Pureuavin Submarine, at Pier 3 Naval Station, Norfolk Virginia. Mr Hargrave had attached refueling hoses to the submarine and began pumping diesel fuel to the submarine. The submarine had an overboard discharge valve open and fuel was discharged into the Elizabeth River. Commander Hamilton, Commanding Officer Naval Submarine Support Center, Norfolk Naval Station said that he would notify and report to approiate authorities since the discharge was a result of the Submarine Anto Fagasta, and not Oil Transport Inc.
column169: There is no recommendations that I can make. My operator followed company policies and procedures. This company has a waterfront policy that has been approved by the United States Coast Guard and was followed.

column168: Officers responded to the scene of a single vehicle traffic accident at the intersection Portfield Highway and West Main Street.  Dispatch advised that a tanker truck had turned over and was leaking fuel.  Upon arrival there was a large amount of diesel fuel that had already leaked onto the road and was running toward the drain next to First Bank and Trust Company.  The Fire Department was called to the scene to attempt to contain the spill.  The FD attempted to divert the spill from anymore gas going into the drain.  Buchanan Oil Corporation is the company that Mr. Whitt was driving for.  Buchanan Oil was contacted and advised of the situation. Employee Chris contact Scott Branham and they advised they were getting their clean up crew to come to the scene.  Mr. Whitt stated that he was going through the red light at approximately 30-35 mph and lost control of the vehicle and it turned over.  There were two point on the trailer where the fuel was leaking, at the front of the trailer near the cab and also at the back of the trailer.

column168: On or around 11/12/2004 a shipment traveling on MAWB 1331-JAL-3687-8586 was routed from SGN-KIX-OKC. This shipment was transferred to DL in a manner that would not have required inspection prior to transport. All packages appeared in good condition and air worthy. Upon arriving in Oklahoma City, after being transported on several Delta flights and transferred to a bonded warehouse, U.S. Customs inspected the shipment and seized it for further analysis. After further review and some time had passed, U.S. Customs agent Tom Pomelow informed OKC cargo that Butane lighters were found in this shipment. This notification to Delta was made near the end of March 2005. At that time Delta's Corporate office was notified and the process to report to FAA was started. FAA agent Bob Bergen was notified via phone of the incident. The shipment had been destroyed by U.S. Customs; however pictures were obtained by Delta prior to that. Agent Bergen and Delta's Corporate Dangerous Goods group informed OKC of the necessity to complete the 5800.1 report.
column169: Delta was not aware of this situation until U.S. Customs notified us of their findings. Delta followed all current U.S. security measures in place prior to transport of this shipment. there were no red flags on this shipment that would have indicated a closer look was necessary.

column168: DRIVER WAS WEST BOUND ON I-10 AND TOOK THE I-610 EXIT GOING SOUTH. WHEN SHE GOT ON 610 FROM THE RAMP, THE UNIT WENT OVER INTO THE LEFT LANE OF 2 LANES AND THE UNIT LAID OVER ON TOP OF THE CENTER DIVIDER AND THE TRAILER SLID DOWN THE DIVIDER HITTING A STEEL IBEAM THAT HOLDS UP THE ROAD SIGNS THAT GOES ACROSS THE NORTH BOUND LANES.  THERE WAS DAMAGE TO THE IBEAM AND IT HAD TO BE TAKEN DOWN. THE COLLISION WITH THE WALL AND IBEAM TORE HOLES IN THE SIDE OF TRAILER AND ALL THE PRODUCT CAME OUT. IT WENT DOWN THE DRAINS AND WAS IN 6 LANES OF THE ROAD. 3527GAL.     GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL DID THE CLEAN UP. THE PRODUCT WAS PRESSURE WASHED AND HIGH PRESSURE WASHED WITH FIRE HOSES. VACUUM TRUCKS WERE BROUGHT OUT TO SUCK UP THE PRODUCT WITH WATER.  THE MANHOLE DRAINS WERE SUCKED OUT. THERE WERE 3 OR 4 TRACTOR TRAILER TRUCKS FROM BEELINE, GULF COAST VACUUM 3 AND BAIC HAS 1 SMALL TRUCK, NOT A TRACTOR TRAILER. GULF COAST 800-997-1744. BAIC 281-471-0400.     GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL ALONG WITH MEMBERS OF THE COAST GUARD MONITORED THE WATER FLOW INTO THE SHIP CHANNEL TO MAKE SURE NONE OF THE CHEMICAL REACHED THE WATERWAY.  PH TESTS WERE PERFORMED 1/4 MILE DOWNSTREAM FROM THE ACCIDENT SCENE WHICH INDICATED THE CHEMICAL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN A 200 YARD AREA.  THE PH TESTING WAS REPEATED THOUGHOUT THE DAY UNTIL THE CLEANUP WAS FINISHED.         HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM WERE ON SCENE. TXDOT SAFETY HAZMAT SUSAN HOOD.   LANE WALKER EMERGENCY RESPONSE WITH TCEQ. THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 52,500 GAL OF WATER PUT IN FRAC TANKS.  THE ROAD SIGNS WERE TAKEN DOWN BY MCREE CRANE AND RIGGING CO. DAN WHEELER HAD 3 WRECKERS.      DRIVER WAS TREATED AND RELEASED AT ST JOSEPH HOSPITAL WHO WOULD NOT DO THE DRUG TEST WITHOUT APPROVAL FAXED TO THEM SO THE DRIVER WAS SENT TO BAYTOWN AND THE POST ACCIDENT DRUG AND ALCOHOL TESTS WERE DONE THERE.
column169: A satellite message was sent out to all of our tractors informing them of this dangerous interchange with instructions to stay away from this area and to utilize the toll bridge to avoid this area.  If they had to exit from I-10 to I-610 South, to slow down to at least 30mph.        The posted speed limit in this area is 40mph.  The concrete barriers that TXDOT are using curve to the left then sharply back to the right creating a rollover hazard for liquid bulk trucks with a sloshing load.  Numerous osbervations were made of other tractor trailers crossing the lane divider as they merged onto I-610 South that could be avoided by straighting the on ramp to merge gradually.

column168: Upon arrival of Flight 64 in Petersburg, the ramp crew opened the forward pit door to begin unloading bags from pit 3. A thick, white foamy substance was found near the door and running forward into pit 1. The pit 1 net was taken down and some boxes and bags were removed. Two 1-gallon plastic containers of Nu-Brite being shipped to Wrangell were discovered, one container was sitting upright on the floor, the other container was near the bulkhead positioned on its side, stacked about half way up from the floor. The solution apparently leaked from this container, as a subsequent review of the caps revealed a damaged, wet seal under the cap of the container that had been found on its side. Alaska Airlines Maintenance Control and Environmental Affairs were contacted after consulting with the Pilot-In-Command. An Alaska Airlines mechanic was dispatched to Petersburg from Juneau. Everything was removed from pits 1-2, and as directed, the mechanic inspected the pits, then neutralized the contaminated areas with mild acid, then wiped the pits with clean water. We estimate less than a cup leaked during transport.  - David Nielsen  Customer Service Manager  Petersburg, AK   907-772-3328

ONYX SERVICES WAS CONTRACTED TO TO FURTHER INSPECT AND REPAIR THE CAR BEFORE MOVING IT TO DESTINATION.  ONYX RETRIEVED A REPLACEMENT VALVE FROM UNION TANK CAR AND REPLACED THE DEFECTIVE VALVE ON TOP OF NATX 38354.  AFTER THE DEFECTIVE VALVE WAS REMOVED IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE GASKET ON THE VACCUM RELIEF DEVICE WAS TORN.

column168: AT 05:15 PM ON 05/09/05 FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT JAMES QUINTIN, SENIOR MANAGER TERMINAL OPERATIONS, ADVISED A SWITCH CREW HAD REPORTED A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR DOWX 6776.  AFTER BEING NOTIFIED, MGR. LERCH CONTACTED DENNIS WOOSTER, EMERGENCY COORDINATOR FOR DOW CHEMICAL, AND ADVISED HIM OF THE REPORTED ODOR.  MR. WOOSTER RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE CAR.  AT 04:53 PM, MR. WOOSTER ADVISED MGR. LERCH, THAT THERE WAS A SLIGHT AMOUNT OF PRODUCT AROUND THE NECK OF BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP, AND THAT THE CAP WAS LOOSE APPROXIMATELY 1/4 TURN.  ALL VALVES ON CAR WERE NOTED TO BE SECURE.  AFTER WOOSTER WIPED AND TIGHTENED THE CAP, THE CAR WAS SECURED, AND RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION.  THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES, DRAINS, OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

column168: AT 04:34 PM ON 05/05/05, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC, AND ADVISED THAT MIKE BREAZEALE, MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS ADVISED TRAIN CREW HAD REPORTED TANK CAR GLNX 23184 TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT FROM TOP OF THE CAR WHILE BEING SWITCHED.  CAR HAD BEEN ISOLATED IN TRACK 9, SETTEGAST YARD.  MGR. LERCH RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT HAD BEEN SPILLED ONTO THE SIDES OF THE CAR, HOWEVER PRODUCT HAD EVAPORATED, AND REQUIRED NO CLEAN-UP.  ADDITIONALLY, THERE WAS NO PRODUCT ON THE GROUND, AND NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED.  INSPECTION OF THE CAR NOTED THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS: ONE OF EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS WAS NOTED IN THE DOWN POSITION, WITH THE REMAINING SEVEN SWINGBOLTS IN POSITION, FINGER TIGHT.  THE ONE INCH AIR BALL VALVE WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION, WITH THE SAFETY PLUG HANGING FROM THE SAFETY CHAIN AND NOT SECURED INTO THE VALVE.  INSPECTION OF THE MANWAY GASKET REVEALED IT TO BE INTACT.  AFTER POSITIONING AND TIGHTENING MANWAY SWINGBOLTS, CLOSING THE AIR VALVE, AND SECURING THE AIR VALVE PLUG, THE CAR WAS SECURED, AND RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION WITH FURTHER INCIDENT.  ON 05/06/05, MGR. LERCH CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, AND SPOKE TO JUDSON BROWN, MGR. OF RAILS SVCS, STOLT NIELSEN TRANSPORTATION, ADVISING HIM OF THE NOTED THE EXCEPTIONS.  MR. BROWN INDICATED THE THIS LOAD WAS A 2ND PARTY LOADING, AND THE ORIGINAL LOADER WAS ALASCO PRODUCTS, INC. OF HOUSTON, TX.  MR BROWN INDICATED THAT HE WOULD CONTACT THE ORIGINATING LOADER, AND CORRECTIVE ACTION WOULD BE TAKEN.  ON 5-12-05, MGR. LERCH, MR. BROWN AND MATTHEW DOWELL, OPERATIONS MGR. FOR ALASCO PRODUCTS, INC. MET AND DISCUSSED CORRECTIVE ACTIONS AND PROPER SECUREMENT PROCEDURES.  MR. DOWELL WAS ALSO PROVIDED A COPY OF THE BOE PAMPHLET 34: RECOMMENDED METHODS FOR THE SAFE LOADING AND UNLOADING OF NON-PRESSURE TANK CARS.  ORIGINAL SEALS PROTECTING MANWAY: CAMIN# 014222, 730, 710, 010928.  SEALS APPLIED: MANWAY: UPRR CTS 0008775.  COMBINATION HOUSING: UPRR CTS 0008776.

column168: REPORT 05192005080 ISSUED FROM CHEMTREC.  RAILROAD EMPLOYEE STATES THAT PRODUCT CAN BE SMELLED FROM VICINITY OF RAILCAR CITX 35247.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES.  HULCHER SERVICES CONTRACTED TO INSPECT CAR.  THEY FOUND THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE WAS LEAKING VAPOR INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  MINIMAL VAPOR LOSS.  PRD GIVEN TEMPORARY REPAIR ON SCENE.  O-RINGS CHANGED, VALVE SHIMMED WITH WASHERS TO CLOSE.  THIS TEMPORARY REPAIR STOPPED THE LEAK.  NO VAPOR ODORS DETECTED.  A WATER LEAK TEST CONDUCTED AND FOUND PRD WORKING PROPERLY.  THE RAILCAR WAS FORWARDED IN TRANSPORTATION.

WILBERT WARNER WAS BEGINNING TO LOAD TURPENTINE AT INTERNATIONAL PAPER IN GEORGETOWN, SC.  AS HE BEGAN TO LOAD HE NOTICED PRODUCT COMING OUT AT THE GATE VALVE.  HE STOPPED LOADING IMMEDIATELY.  THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS NOT SEATED CORRECTLY.  APPARENTLY A PIECE OF TRASH OR AIR POCKET WAS INSIDE THE INTERNAL VALVE.  HE RAISED THE INTERNAL VALVE AND CLOSED IT AGAIN AND THE INTERNAL THEN SEATED CORRECTLY.  APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS SPILLED INSIDE THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  PLANT PERSONNEL WASHED DOWN THE CONTAINMENT AREA.
column169: WHEN THE TRAILER CAME BACK TO JACKSONVILLE, SHOP PERSONNEL INSPECTED THE INTERNAL VALVE.  WE THEN CLEANED THE TANK INTERNALLY.  THE TRAILER FOUND TO BE WORKING PROPERLY.

PACKAGE WAS FOUND GIVING OFF A STRONG ODOR & LEAKING.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER PACKAGES WE FOUND WHAT APPEARED TO BE INAPPROPRIATE PACKAGING, WHEREIN THERE WAS INSUFFICENT ABSORBANT MATERIAL SURROUNDING THE GLASS BOTTLES.  IN ADDITION, ICAO PACKING INSTRUCTION 819 REQUIRES AN INTERMEDIATE PACKAGING WHEN GLASS INNER BOTTLES ARE UTILIZED.  THERE WAS NO INTERMEDIATE PACKAGING INSIDE THE OUTER BOX.  UPON FURTHER DISCUSSION WITH THE SHIPPER, A MAGNABLEND EMPLOYEE NAMED TIFFANY WILLIAMS, A LAB TECH, PACKAGED THIS DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT WHEN IN FACT SHE HAD NO DG TRAINING.  I SPOKE TO JOHNNY CATHEY, FROM THE RECIPIENT, HALIBURTON.  HALIBURTON'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE PHONE # WAS USED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER.  THE SHIPPER DID NOT HAVE AUTHORIZATION TO USE THAT PHONE NUMBER (800-666-9260).  I HAVE REQUESTED PACKAGE TEST REPORTS FROM THE SHIPPER, WHO WAS DUBIOUS AS TO WHETHER OR NOT THEY ACTUALLY EXISTED.  FEDEX EXPRESS HAS EMBARGOED THIS SHIPPER FROM OFFERING ANY MORE DANGEROUS GOODS UNTIL THE TRAINING AND PACKAGE TEST ISSUES ARE RESOLVED.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD IN LAWTON, OK FOR AN FAA INSPECTION.  I SPOKE TO SA BRYAN BUCHANAN IN DFW ON 5/27/05.

column168: THE FOLLOWING IS A STATEMENT CONCERNING THE INCIDENT THAT OCCURRED ON 5/19/05 AT PRAXAIR DISTRIBUTION INC. BROOKFIELD WI.  I CONTACTED THE NIGHT SUPERVISOR FOR THE REVIEW OF THE PAPERWORK.  THEN PROCEEDED TO POSITION THE DELIVERY VEHICLE (7528) DIRECTLY BEHIND THE RECEPTACLE (7260).  I INSTALLED THE DELIVERY CONNECTOR TO 7260 AND THE DELIVERY HOSE FROM 7528.  AFTER THE APPROPRIATE PUMP COOL DOWN PERIOD, I DELIVERED 453000 CU FT INTO 7260.  UPON COMPLETION OF THE DELIVERY, I SHUT OFF THE PUMP AND CLOSED THE DELIVERY VALVE AND PB VALVE ON 7528.  I THEN RECORDED THE LEVEL GAGE AND PRESSURE READINGS FROM 7260.  ONCE THE CORRECT PRESSURE WAS REACHED IN 7260 I CLOSED THE VENT VALE AND TAPPED THE HOSE CONNECTION WITH MY HAMMER.  I IMMMEDIATELY REALIZED I HAD NOT CLOSED THE FILL VALVE ON 7260, SO I CLIMBED ONTO THE STEP AT THE BACK OF THE TRAILER AND BEGAN TO CLOSE THE VALVE.  SUDDENLY THERE WAS A LOUD BANG TO MY LEFT AND I WAS THROWN FROM THE TRAILER STEP.  I LANDED ON MY HANDS AND KNEES ON THE GROUND AND BECAME VARY AWARE OF A LOUD ROARING SOUND BEHIND ME.  I SCRAMBLED TO MY FEET AND VERY QUICKLY MOVED AWAY FROM THE NOISE.  WHEN I TURNED AROUND BOTH 7528 AND 7260 WHERE BEING ENGULFED IN A LARGE WHITE CLOUD OF PRODUCT.  I RAN INTO THE BUILDING, FOUND THE NIGHT SUPERVISOR (JAKE) AND INFORMED HIM OF THE SITUATION.  WE BOTH WENT BACK OUTSIDE TO FIND THE ENTIRE PARKING AREA COVERED BY THE CLOUD.  JAKE WENT BACK INTO THE BUILDING TO CLOSE ANY OPEN DOORS ON THE SIDE OF THE PRODUCT LEAK.  I MADE FEW EFFORTS TO RETRIEVE MY PHONE FROM THE TRACTOR, BUT AT FIRST I COULDN'T FIND THE TRACTOR IN THE CLOUD.  FINALLY A BREEZE BLEW THE CLOUD FAR ENOUGH BACK SO THE I COULD GET IN TO THE TRUCK AND GET THE PHONE.  I CALLED CUSTOMER SERVICE AND INFORMED THEM IF THE INCIDENT IN PROGRESS AND THAT TRAILER TIRES MAY NEED TO BE REPLACED.  I THEN CALLED PRAXAIR DISPATCH AND INFORMED THEM OF THE SITUATION, AND THAT I WAS UNHARMED BUT I WASN'T SURE ABOUT EQUIPMENT.  I ALSO CALLED DENNIS KURTS IN THE HOPES OF FINDING ANY IDEAS TO STOP THE LEAKAGE.  I KEPT PACING BACK AND FORTH ACROSS THE FRONT OF THE DELIVERY UNIT TRYING TO FIND A WAY TO STOP THE LEAK.  A GOOD 35 TO 40 MINUTES PASSED WITH PRODUCT LEAKING FROM 7260.  THE CLOUD CONTINUED TO COVER THE ENTIRE PARKING AREA AT PDI AS WELL AS FLOATING ACROSS I-94.  JAKE INFORMED ME THAT HE HAD CALLED EMERGENCY SERVICES AND SAFETY TEAM FOR PDI.  DURING MY SECOND CALL TO MARK NELSON A BREEZE BLEW THE CLOUD AWAY FROM THE BACK OF THE TWO TRAILERS.  I COULD PLAINLY SEE THE PRODUCT SQUIRTING FROM THE TRAILER THE VALVE THAT NEEDED TO BE CLOSED.  I TOOK THIS OPPORTUNITY TO RUSH IN AND CLOSE THE VALVE, STOPPING THE LEAK.  SEEING THE STUB PORTION OF THE FILL COUPLING STILL IN THE THREADS OF MY DELIVERY HOSE I QUICKLY DISASSEMBLED IT FEARING IT WOULD SEIZE IN THE HOSE AND I WOULDN'T BE ABLE TO REMOVE IT FOR HOURS.  BY THIS TIME THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD SHOWN UP AND I EXPLAINED THE SITUATION TO THEM, AND OFFERED WHATEVER INFORMATION THEY REQUESTED.  I

column168: LAURA, CHEMTREC, REPORTED A TRUCK DRIVER FOR AMERICAN PACIFIC WAS DELIVERING CONTAINER TRIU 933506, LOADED WITH POLYMERIC BEADS, TO THE LATC RAIL YARD, LOS ANGELES, CA., WHEN HE CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE CONTAINERS PRODUCT. column168: ON MAY 24TH, 2005, AN A.R. PAQUETTE COMPANY, INC. TRANSPORT TRUCK WAS INVOLVED IN AN INCIDENT AT THE INTERSECTION OF INTERSTATE HIGHWAY 20 (IH20) AND INTERSTATE HIGHWAY 45 (IH45) IN SOUTHEAST DALLAS (DALLAS COUNTY), TEXAS.  THE TRUCK, TRANSPORTING WASTE FOR UNIVAR USA, INC., WAS TRAVELING WEST ON IH20 AND APPARENTLY LOST CONTROL, STRUCK A STRUCTURAL OVERPASS COLUMN AND BECAME FULLY INVOLVED BY FIRE.  THE DALLAS FIRE DEPARTMENT IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT FOLLOWED BY AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE BY TAS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, L.P. (TAS).  ON THE DAY OF THE INCIDENT, TAS ADDRESSED THE EMERGENCY ASPECTS OF SECURING THE HAZARDOUS CARGO, LIMITING FURTHER CHEMICAL IMPACT TO HUMAN HEALTH/ENVIRONMENT ALONG WITH INITIAL TASKS OF RESTRICTING THE MOVEMENT OF CONTAMINATED FIRE SUPRESSION WATER, REMOVAL AND CONTAINMENT OF CONTAMINATED WATER, AND REMOVAL OF DEBRIS TO ALLOW RE-OPENING OF THE ROADWAY.  TAS MET WITH REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE TEXAS COMMISSION ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (TCEQ) AND THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (TXDOT) ON MAY 26TH, 2005 TO PROVIDE GUIDANCE AND DISCUSS FURTHER CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES.  MR. JAN MALONE AND MR. JAMES KIRLIND, OF THE TCEQ REGION 4 EMERGENCY RESPONSE & STRIKE TEAM, DIRECTED FIELD SOIL SAMPLING EFFORTS IN THE AREAS IMPACTED BY THE RELEASED CHEMICAL AND CONTAMINATED FIRE SUPPRESSION WATER.  TXDOT ENVIRONMENTAL STAFF (CHRISTOPHER TOLAR AND JIM CRISP OF THE DALLAS DISTRICT) CONCURRED WITH THE ASSESSMENT EFFORTS CONSIDERED AND REQUESTED COORDINATION AND NOTIFICATION OF EFFORTS THROUGH THE DISTRICT OFFICE.  TAS IMMEDIATELY BEGAN THE SURFACE SOIL SAMPLING EFFORT ON MAY 26TH IN ACCORDANCE WITH TCEQ/TXDOT DIRECTIVES.  DATA GATHERED FROM THE ASSESSMENT WERE USED TO IDENTIFY AREAS OF CONCERN AND DETERMINED SOIL REMOVAL REQUIREMENTS.  EFFORTS WERE ALSO BEGUN TO IDENTIFY AREAS OF CONCERN AND DETERMINED SOIL REMOVAL REQUIREMENTS.  EFFORTS WERE ALSO BEGUN TO IDENTIFY AND CHARACTERIZE SOIL REMOVAL REQUIREMENTS.  EFFORTS WERE ALSO BEGUN TO IDENTIFY AND CHARACTERIZE THE REMAINING FREIGHT WASTE FOR APPROPRIATE DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS.  ADDITIONAL TASKS DIRECTED BY TXDOT REGARDING IMPACTS TO THE STRUCTURE BY FIRE WERE ALSO ESTABLISHED.  THE FOLLOWING REPORT SECTIONS ADDRESS THE SPECIFIC ACTIVITIES CONDUCTED BY TAS ALONG WITH SCHEDULES AND DISPOSAL DOCUMENTATION.

column168: ON MAY 24TH, 2005, AN A.R. PAQUETTE COMPANY, INC. TRANSPORT TRUCK WAS INVOLVED IN AN INCIDENT AT THE INTERSECTION OF INTERSTATE HIGHWAY 20 (IH20) AND INTERSTATE HIGHWAY 45 (IH45) IN SOUTHEAST DALLAS (DALLAS COUNTY), TEXAS.  THE TRUCK, TRANSPORTING WASTE FOR UNIVAR USA, INC., WAS TRAVELING WEST ON IH20 AND APPARENTLY LOST CONTROL, STRUCK A STRUCTURAL OVERPASS COLUMN AND BECAME FULLY INVOLVED BY FIRE.  THE DALLAS FIRE DEPARTMENT IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT FOLLOWED BY AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE BY TAS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, L.P. (TAS).  ON THE DAY OF THE INCIDENT, TAS ADDRESSED THE EMERGENCY ASPECTS OF SECURING THE HAZARDOUS CARGO, LIMITING FURTHER CHEMICAL IMPACT TO HUMAN HEALTH/ENVIRONMENT ALONG WITH INITIAL TASKS OF RESTRICTING THE MOVEMENT OF CONTAMINATED FIRE SUPRESSION WATER, REMOVAL AND CONTAINMENT OF CONTAMINATED WATER, AND REMOVAL OF DEBRIS TO ALLOW RE-OPENING OF THE ROADWAY.  TAS MET WITH REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE TEXAS COMMISSION ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (TCEQ) AND THE TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (TXDOT) ON MAY 26TH, 2005 TO PROVIDE GUIDANCE AND DISCUSS FURTHER CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES.  MR. JAN MALONE AND MR. JAMES KIRLIND, OF THE TCEQ REGION 4 EMERGENCY RESPONSE & STRIKE TEAM, DIRECTED FIELD SOIL SAMPLING EFFORTS IN THE AREAS IMPACTED BY THE RELEASED CHEMICAL AND CONTAMINATED FIRE SUPPRESSION WATER.  TXDOT ENVIRONMENTAL STAFF (CHRISTOPHER TOLAR AND JIM CRISP OF THE DALLAS DISTRICT) CONCURRED WITH THE ASSESSMENT EFFORTS CONSIDERED AND REQUESTED COORDINATION AND NOTIFICATION OF EFFORTS THROUGH THE DISTRICT OFFICE.  TAS IMMEDIATELY BEGAN THE SURFACE SOIL SAMPLING EFFORT ON MAY 26TH IN ACCORDANCE WITH TCEQ/TXDOT DIRECTIVES.  DATA GATHERED FROM THE ASSESSMENT WERE USED TO IDENTIFY AREAS OF CONCERN AND DETERMINED SOIL REMOVAL REQUIREMENTS.  EFFORTS WERE ALSO BEGUN TO IDENTIFY AREAS OF CONCERN AND DETERMINED SOIL REMOVAL REQUIREMENTS.  EFFORTS WERE ALSO BEGUN TO IDENTIFY AND CHARACTERIZE SOIL REMOVAL REQUIREMENTS.  EFFORTS WERE ALSO BEGUN TO IDENTIFY AND CHARACTERIZE THE REMAINING FREIGHT WASTE FOR APPROPRIATE DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS.  ADDITIONAL TASKS DIRECTED BY TXDOT REGARDING IMPACTS TO THE STRUCTURE BY FIRE WERE ALSO ESTABLISHED.  THE FOLLOWING REPORT SECTIONS ADDRESS THE SPECIFIC ACTIVITIES CONDUCTED BY TAS ALONG WITH SCHEDULES AND DISPOSAL DOCUMENTATION.

JAMES KIRLIND, OF THE TCEQ REGION 4 EMERGENCY RESPONSE & STRIKE TEAM, DIRECTED FIELD SOIL SAMPLING EFFORTS IN THE AREAS IMPACTED BY THE RELEASED CHEMICAL AND CONTAMINATED FIRE SUPPRESSION WATER.  TXDOT ENVIRONMENTAL STAFF (CHRISTOPHER TOLAR AND JIM CRISP OF THE DALLAS DISTRICT) CONCURRED WITH THE ASSESSMENT EFFORTS CONSIDERED AND REQUESTED COORDINATION AND NOTIFICATION OF EFFORTS THROUGH THE DISTRICT OFFICE.  TAS IMMEDIATELY BEGAN THE SURFACE SOIL SAMPLING EFFORT ON MAY 26TH IN ACCORDANCE WITH TCEQ/TXDOT DIRECTIVES.  DATA GATHERED FROM THE ASSESSMENT WERE USED TO IDENTIFY AREAS OF CONCERN AND DETERMINED SOIL REMOVAL REQUIREMENTS.  EFFORTS WERE ALSO BEGUN TO IDENTIFY AREAS OF CONCERN AND DETERMINED SOIL REMOVAL REQUIREMENTS.  EFFORTS WERE ALSO BEGUN TO IDENTIFY AND CHARACTERIZE SOIL REMOVAL REQUIREMENTS.  EFFORTS WERE ALSO BEGUN TO IDENTIFY AND CHARACTERIZE THE REMAINING FREIGHT WASTE FOR APPROPRIATE DISPOSAL ARRANGEMENTS.  ADDITIONAL TASKS DIRECTED BY TXDOT REGARDING IMPACTS TO THE STRUCTURE BY FIRE WERE ALSO ESTABLISHED.  THE FOLLOWING REPORT SECTIONS ADDRESS THE SPECIFIC ACTIVITIES CONDUCTED BY TAS ALONG WITH SCHEDULES AND DISPOSAL DOCUMENTATION.
column169: IN-HOUSE TRAINING FOR ALL DRIVERS SHOWING IMPROPER USE OF OFF-TIME COULD CAUSE DRIVER ERROR.  A DRIVER WITH TWO DAYS OFF SHOULD REST BEFORE COMING BACK ON DUTY.

column168: ON MAY 24TH, 2005, AN A.R. PAQUETTE COMPANY, INC. TRANSPORT TRUCK WAS INVOLVED IN AN INCIDENT AT THE INTERSECTION OF INTERSTATE HIGHWAY 20 (IH20) AND INTERSTATE HIGHWAY 45 (IH45) IN SOUTHEAST DALLAS (DALLAS COUNTY), TEXAS.  THE TRUCK, TRANSPORTING WASTE FOR UNIVAR USA, INC., WAS TRAVELING WEST ON IH20 AND APPARENTLY LOST CONTROL, STRUCK A STRUCTURAL OVERPASS COLUMN AND BECAME FULLY INVOLVED BY FIRE.  THE DALLAS FIRE DEPARTMENT IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT FOLLOWED BY AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE BY TAS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, L.P. (TAS).
